:"1296","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cotton Hall, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Landwade, Cambridge, England":"Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Humphrey Cotton was born about 1296, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Cotton, was 23 and his mother, Magelena Forbe, was 23. He married Anne Holbroke in 1325, in Cambridgeshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1363, in Landwade, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"Abt 1296–1363":"umbes 1296–1363","1296–1363":"1296–1363","1305–1376":"1305–1376","1335–1397":"1335–1397","1275–1342":"1275–1342","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","Abt 1296":"umbes 1296","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1376":"1376","1342":"1342","1397":"1397","1363":"1363","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cotton Hall, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Landwade, Cambridge, England":"Landwade, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1296–1363":"noin 1296–1363","1296–1363":"1296–1363","1305–1376":"1305–1376","1335–1397":"1335–1397","1275–1342":"1275–1342","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","Abt 1296":"noin 1296","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1376":"1376","1342":"1342","1397":"1397","1363":"1363","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cotton Hall, Cambridge, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","Cotton Hall, Landwade, Cambridge, Engla